Document: Using the Web editor  
Path: godot/tutorials/editor/using_the_web_editor.rst  
Summary: Introduces the Godot Web editor and its current status as a preliminary tool.  

The Web editor is available at https://editor.godotengine.org/ and can be used for new or existing projects. Note: The web editor is in a preliminary stage. While its feature set may be sufficient for educational purposes, it is currently not recommended for production work. See doc_using_the_web_editor_limitations below.
---CHUNK---
Document: Using the Web Editor
Path: godot/tutorials/editor/using_the_web_editor.rst
Summary: Browser requirements and limitations for the Godot Web editor

The Web editor requires support for WebAssembly's SharedArrayBuffer to enable threading in the browser. Supported browsers can be found in the system requirements documentation. Mobile browsers are technically supported but will have performance and input limitations that make them unsuitable for most development tasks.

The web editor only supports the Compatibility renderer due to current limitations in running Vulkan applications on web platforms. For optimal performance, consider using a Chromium-based browser if experiencing issues in Firefox, as these browsers generally perform better with WebGL applications.

Note: Firefox may have performance issues with the Web editor, and switching to a Chromium-based browser is recommended for better WebGL performance.
---CHUNK---
Document: Using the Web Editor
Path: godot/tutorials/editor/using_the_web_editor.rst
Summary: Steps to import an existing project into the Godot Web Editor and important folder placement guidelines

To import an existing project into the Godot Web Editor:
- Specify a ZIP file to preload on the HTML5 filesystem using the Preload project ZIP input
- Run the editor by clicking Start Godot editor. The Godot Project Manager should appear after 10-20 seconds. On slower machines or connections, loading may take up to a minute
- In the dialog that appears at the middle of the window, specify a name for the folder to create then click the Create Folder button (it doesn't have to match the ZIP archive's name)
- Click Install & Edit and the project will open in the editor

Note: It's important to place the project folder somewhere in /home/web_user/. If your project folder is placed outside /home/web_user/, you will lose your project when closing the editor! When you follow the steps described above, the project folder will always be located in /home/web_user/projects, keeping it safe.
---CHUNK---
Document: using_the_web_editor  
Path: godot/tutorials/editor/using_the_web_editor.rst  
Summary: Explains how the web editor handles project execution within a single window using tabs instead of separate windows.  

Editing and running a project in the web editor differs from the native version. The web editor is confined to a single window and cannot open new windows when running projects. When you click the Run button or press F5, the project will appear to "replace" the editor window.  

The web editor provides an alternative approach by using tabs for the editor and game views. You can switch between the Editor and Game tabs using buttons at the top of the interface. To close the running game or editor, click the × button next to the respective tabs. This tab-based system allows you to manage both the development environment and the running project within the same window without requiring additional screen space.
---CHUNK---
Document: using_the_web_editor  
Path: godot/tutorials/editor/using_the_web_editor.rst  
Summary: Explains how project files are stored in the Web Editor and how to download them as a ZIP archive.  

Due to browser security limitations, the editor will save project files to the browser's IndexedDB storage. This storage isn't accessible as a regular folder on your machine but is abstracted away in a database. You can download the project files as a ZIP archive by using Project > Tools > Download Project Source. This can be used to export the project using a native Godot editor since exporting from the web editor isn't supported yet.  

Note: Future implementations may use the HTML5 FileSystem API to store project files on the user's filesystem as the native editor would do. However, this isn't implemented yet.